text.tspan: Sonder is a Multiplayer Roguelike taking inspiration from
survival games like DayZ and roguelikes like Spelunky.

flowRoot.flowPara: As monsters are killed, treasures are taken, and players progress past an island an island will begin to fall into the abyss. After a hectic collapsing period a new island with fresh monsters and treasures will rise from the abyss to take its place.

Clouds over an island indicate that an event is occuring there. Events range from negative to positive and include things like boss fights, hidden treasures, and poisonous gas. The purpose of these is to gather players and give the option of risky gameplay.

Although far islands will appear as just a simplified version, information on the island's difficulty can be assessed by the theme of the island (i.e. Grasslands, Ruins, Tundra). These will all offer different levels of platforming, combat, and rewards.

Paths between two islands signify that a portal connects. To simplify programming and ensure that only one island is loaded at any given time, portals are the only way to travel between islands. Certain poortals may also have some cost associated with them.
The world consists of a shell of floating islands. As players join and leave the world, the radius of the shell will increase and new islands will be added to keep a consistent player density.

One key element unique to Sonder is a focus on platforming and movement. This is to add depth to decision making and the game from being a "walking Many elements of the game will be designed with the platforming system in mind.

Rather than quick-death gun play, Sonder will be more of a close-range, higher-health combat system. This is to make fights seem more fair and deaths more long-time-coming. Managing health in and out of combat will be critical for successs.
The game has simplified progression system where the player

As a roguelike, players will need to adapt to the randomized items given to them to overcome the randomized threats presented to them. Learning to deal with these and fast adaption are perhaps more important than the mechanics of platforming and combat.
